{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775890018296,"sessionID":"ses_284b6dcd9ffeKUGA3ZF6QyYYPP","part":{"id":"prt_d7b4b2fdd001A8Xc7TFiZ3h6oa","messageID":"msg_d7b4a7348001bYR697f4bGa4c8","sessionID":"ses_284b6dcd9ffeKUGA3ZF6QyYYPP","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-a7f933c46c1e4d0d8c4ece899f362a61","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Delta Specification — AR-037 PCAP 分析器示例应用\n\n## AR Metadata\n- **AR ID**: AR-037\n- **Title**: PCAP 分析器示例应用\n- **Module**: example\n- **Language**: Python\n- **Size**: M\n- **Status**: Implementation Required\n\n## Purpose\n\nDemonstrate AgentCube Python SDK usage by implementing a PCAP (packet capture) analyzer that uploads PCAP files to a Code Interpreter session, installs analysis libraries, executes analysis scripts, and returns insights about network traffic.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Environment setup for PCAP analysis\n\nThe system SHALL prepare the Code Interpreter environment with necessary PCAP analysis libraries (scapy, pyshark, matplotlib, pandas) before performing any analysis.\n\n#### Scenario: Install scapy library\n\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n- **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n- **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install scapy` and verify installation by importing scapy successfully\n\n#### Scenario: Install pyshark library\n\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n- **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n- **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install pyshark` and verify installation by importing pyshark successfully\n\n#### Scenario: Install visualization libraries\n\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n- **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n- **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install matplotlib pandas` for data visualization and analysis\n\n#### Scenario: Handle installation failures\n\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n- **WHEN** pip installation fails for any required library\n- **THEN** the system SHALL log the error and raise `CommandExecutionError` with details about which library failed to install\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: PCAP file upload\n\nThe system SHALL provide functionality to upload local PCAP files to the Code Interpreter session for analysis.\n\n#### Scenario: Upload single PCAP file\n\n- **GIVEN** a local PCAP file exists at `/local/path/capture.pcap`\n- **WHEN** `upload_pcap_file(local_path, remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** the file SHALL be uploaded to the remote Code Interpreter environment at the specified remote path\n\n#### Scenario: Upload multiple PCAP files\n\n- **GIVEN** multiple local PCAP files exist\n- **WHEN** `upload_pcap_files(file_list, remote_directory)` is called\n- **THEN** all files SHALL be uploaded to the remote directory and a success message SHALL confirm the count of uploaded files\n\n#### Scenario: Verify upload success\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file was uploaded\n- **WHEN** `list_files()` is called on the remote path\n- **THEN** the uploaded file SHALL appear in the file listing\n\n#### Scenario: Handle invalid PCAP file path\n\n- **GIVEN** a local file path does not exist\n- **WHEN** `upload_pcap_file` is called with the invalid path\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `FileNotFoundError` with the invalid path in the error message\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Basic packet statistics\n\nThe system SHALL provide functions to extract basic statistics from PCAP files including packet count, protocols, and time range.\n\n#### Scenario: Count total packets\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded at `/remote/capture.pcap`\n- **WHEN** `analyze_packet_count(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return the total number of packets in the PCAP file\n\n#### Scenario: Identify protocols\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_protocols(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping protocol names (TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.) to packet counts\n\n#### Scenario: Calculate time range\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_time_range(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a tuple containing (start_timestamp, end_timestamp, duration_seconds)\n\n#### Scenario: Protocol distribution summary\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_protocols(remote_path)` returns protocol counts\n- **THEN** the output SHALL include percentage distribution for each protocol\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Top talkers analysis\n\nThe system SHALL identify and rank top communicating IP addresses (both sources and destinations) by packet count and byte count.\n\n#### Scenario: Top source IPs by packet count\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_source_ips(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: Top destination IPs by packet count\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_destination_ips(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: Top IPs by byte count\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_ips_by_bytes(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, byte_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: Bidirectional traffic summary\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_bidirectional_traffic(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary where keys are (source_ip, destination_ip) tuples and values are (packet_count, byte_count) tuples\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Port analysis\n\nThe system SHALL analyze network traffic by port numbers to identify commonly used services and ports.\n\n#### Scenario: Top source ports\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_source_ports(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (port, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: Top destination ports\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_destination_ports(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (port, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: Port-to-service mapping\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_ports_with_services(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of (port, service_name, packet_count) tuples where well-known ports are mapped to common services (HTTP=80, HTTPS=443, DNS=53, etc.)\n\n#### Scenario: Filter by specific port\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `filter_by_port(remote_path, port=443)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return statistics for packets using only that destination port\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Traffic visualization\n\nThe system SHALL generate visualizations of PCAP analysis results including protocol distribution charts and time-series graphs.\n\n#### Scenario: Protocol distribution pie chart\n\n- **GIVEN** protocol analysis data is available\n- **WHEN** `visualize_protocol_distribution(protocol_data)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL generate a pie chart image file showing the percentage of each protocol and return the remote path to the image\n\n#### Scenario: Packets over time line chart\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `visualize_packets_over_time(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL generate a line chart showing packet count per time interval and return the remote path to the image\n\n#### Scenario: Top IPs bar chart\n\n- **GIVEN** top IP analysis data is available\n- **WHEN** `visualize_top_ips(ip_data, title=\"Top IPs\")` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL generate a horizontal bar chart showing top IPs and their packet counts and return the remote path to the image\n\n#### Scenario: Download visualization image\n\n- **GIVEN** a visualization image was generated at `/remote/protocol_distribution.png`\n- **WHEN** `download_file(remote_path, local_path)` is called\n- **THEN** the image SHALL be downloaded to the specified local path\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: HTTP traffic analysis\n\nThe system SHALL extract and analyze HTTP-specific information including URLs, user agents, and status codes.\n\n#### Scenario: Extract HTTP requests\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_http_requests(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of dictionaries containing (method, url, host, user_agent) for each HTTP request\n\n#### Scenario: Extract HTTP responses\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_http_responses(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of dictionaries containing (status_code, content_type, response_length) for each HTTP response\n\n#### Scenario: Count HTTP status codes\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_http_status_codes(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping status codes (200, 404, 500, etc.) to occurrence counts\n\n#### Scenario: Top HTTP hosts\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_http_hosts(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (host, request_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: DNS traffic analysis\n\nThe system SHALL extract and analyze DNS queries and responses to identify queried domains and response types.\n\n#### Scenario: Extract DNS queries\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_dns_queries(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of queried domain names\n\n#### Scenario: Count top queried domains\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_top_dns_domains(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (domain, query_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n\n#### Scenario: DNS response types\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_dns_response_types(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping DNS record types (A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, etc.) to occurrence counts\n\n#### Scenario: DNS resolution failures\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n- **WHEN** `analyze_dns_failures(remote_path)` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a list of domain names that received NXDOMAIN or SERVFAIL responses\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Comprehensive analysis report\n\nThe system SHALL generate a comprehensive markdown or HTML report combining all analysis results.\n\n#### Scenario: Generate markdown report\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file has been fully analyzed\n- **WHEN** `generate_report(analysis_results, output_path, format=\"markdown\")` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL create a markdown file at the specified output path containing sections for basic statistics, top talkers, port analysis, HTTP analysis, DNS analysis, and embedded visualization images\n\n#### Scenario: Generate HTML report\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP file has been fully analyzed\n- **WHEN** `generate_report(analysis_results, output_path, format=\"html\")` is called\n- **THEN** it SHALL create an HTML file at the specified output path with styled sections and embedded visualization images\n\n#### Scenario: Download complete report\n\n- **GIVEN** a report was generated at `/remote/report.md`\n- **WHEN** `download_file(remote_path, local_path)` is called\n- **THEN** the complete report file SHALL be downloaded to the specified local path\n\n#### Scenario: Report includes execution metadata\n\n- **GIVEN** a report is being generated\n- **WHEN** the report is created\n- **THEN** it SHALL include metadata such as file name, analysis timestamp, and total execution time\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Example usage script\n\nThe system SHALL provide a complete example script demonstrating end-to-end usage of the PCAP analyzer with the AgentCube SDK.\n\n#### Scenario: Basic usage example\n\n- **GIVEN** the example script `pcap_analyzer_example.py` exists\n- **WHEN** the script is executed with a sample PCAP file\n- **THEN** it SHALL initialize a `CodeInterpreterClient`, upload the PCAP file, run all analyses, generate a report, and download results\n\n#### Scenario: Example with custom configuration\n\n- **GIVEN** the example script supports configuration parameters\n- **WHEN** run with custom `name`, `namespace`, and `ttl` arguments\n- **THEN** the Code Interpreter session SHALL be created with the specified parameters\n\n#### Scenario: Example handles cleanup\n\n- **GIVEN** the example script completes analysis\n- **WHEN** the script exits (either successfully or with error)\n- **THEN** it SHALL properly clean up by stopping the Code Interpreter session via context manager\n\n#### Scenario: Example error handling\n\n- **GIVEN** the example script encounters an error during analysis\n- **WHEN** an exception occurs\n- **THEN** it SHALL log the error, display a user-friendly message, and exit gracefully\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Code Interpreter session management\n\nThe system SHALL properly manage Code Interpreter sessions including initialization, reuse, and cleanup.\n\n#### Scenario: Reuse existing session\n\n- **GIVEN** a `session_id` is provided to the `CodeInterpreterClient`\n- **WHEN** the client is initialized\n- **THEN** it SHALL connect to the existing session without creating a new one\n\n#### Scenario: Session cleanup on completion\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP analysis completes successfully\n- **WHEN** the analysis script exits the context manager\n- **THEN** the session SHALL be stopped and cleaned up automatically\n\n#### Scenario: Session cleanup on error\n\n- **GIVEN** a PCAP analysis encounters an error\n- **WHEN** the analysis script exits the context manager with an exception\n- **THEN** the session SHALL still be stopped and cleaned up automatically\n\n#### Scenario: Verbose logging\n\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` is set on the `CodeInterpreterClient`\n- **WHEN** operations are performed\n- **THEN** detailed log messages SHALL be output for each operation (upload, execute, download)\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Performance optimization\n\nThe system SHALL handle large PCAP files efficiently with appropriate timeout and resource management.\n\n#### Scenario: Large file timeout handling\n\n- **GIVEN** a large PCAP file (>100MB) is being analyzed\n- **WHEN** analysis operations are executed\n- **THEN** appropriate timeouts SHALL be used for long-running commands and the system SHALL handle timeouts gracefully\n\n#### Scenario: Chunked processing for very large files\n\n- **GIVEN** a very large PCAP file (>1GB) is being analyzed\n- **WHEN** packet analysis runs\n- **THEN** the system SHALL process the file in chunks to avoid memory exhaustion\n\n#### Scenario: Progress reporting for long operations\n\n- **GIVEN** a long-running analysis is in progress\n- **WHEN** the operation takes more than 10 seconds\n- **THEN** the system SHALL log progress messages at regular intervals\n\n#### Scenario: Resource cleanup after analysis\n\n- **GIVEN** analysis of a large file completes\n- **WHEN** the analysis script finishes\n- **THEN** temporary files and resources SHALL be cleaned up in the remote environment\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n\n1. ✅ Code Interpreter environment setup with required libraries\n2. ✅ PCAP file upload functionality (single and multiple files)\n3. ✅ Basic packet statistics (count, protocols, time range)\n4. ✅ Top talkers analysis (source/destination IPs by packet and byte count)\n5. ✅ Port analysis with service mapping\n6. ✅ Traffic visualization (protocol distribution, time series, top IPs)\n7. ✅ HTTP traffic analysis (requests, responses, status codes, hosts)\n8. ✅ DNS traffic analysis (queries, domains, response types, failures)\n9. ✅ Comprehensive report generation (markdown and HTML)\n10. ✅ Example usage script with proper configuration and cleanup\n11. ✅ Code Interpreter session management (reuse, cleanup, logging)\n12. ✅ Performance optimization for large files (timeouts, chunking, progress)\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- `agentcube-sdk>=0.0.10` (CodeInterpreterClient)\n- `scapy>=2.5.0` (PCAP parsing)\n- `pyshark>=0.6` (Wireshark-compatible parsing)\n- `matplotlib>=3.7.0` (visualization)\n- `pandas>=2.0.0` (data analysis)\n- Python >=3.10\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Base Design: `python-sdk/design.md`\n- Base Specification: `python-sdk/spec.md`\n- AR: AR-037 — PCAP 分析器示例应用","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775890018285,"end":1775890018294}}}}
